Data Preparation and Description¶

1.Data: Multi-class classification problem --- 77 attiributes with numerical----

The data set consists of the expression levels of 77 proteins/protein modifications that produced detectable signals in the nuclear fraction of cortex. There are 38 control mice and 34 trisomic mice (Down syndrome), for a total of 72 mice. In the experiments, 15 measurements were registered of each protein per sample/mouse. Therefore, for control mice, there are 38x15, or 570 measurements, and for trisomic mice, there are 34x15, or 510 measurements. The dataset contains a total of 1080 measurements per protein. Each measurement can be considered as an independent sample/mouse.

The eight classes of mice are described based on features such as genotype, behavior and treatment. According to genotype, mice can be control or trisomic. According to behavior, some mice have been stimulated to learn (context-shock) and others have not (shock-context) and in order to assess the effect of the drug memantine in recovering the ability to learn in trisomic mice, some mice have been injected with the drug and others have not.

In [2]:
mice_df = pd.read_excel('D:\\Dersler\\IE 582\\HW4\\Multi-class;categoric+numeric,82\\Data_Cortex_Nuclear.xls',index_col=0)
mice_df.dropna(inplace = True)
mice_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
mice_X = mice_df.iloc[:,0:77]
mice_Y = mice_df.iloc[:,80]
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
mice_Y= pd.DataFrame(label_encoder.fit_transform(np.array(mice_Y)))  ##transform categorical output
##columns 77,78 and 79 are output column define the output 80. 2^3=8 different outputs exist in column 80. They are not needed
#split train and test
mice_X_train, mice_X_test, mice_Y_train, mice_Y_test = train_test_split(mice_X, mice_Y, test_size=0.36, random_state=42)
mice_Y_train = mice_Y_train[0]
mice_Y_test = mice_Y_test[0]

2.Data: Class-imbalance problem ---23 attiributes with numerical and categorical variable----

This research aimed at the case of customers default payments in Taiwan and compares the predictive accuracy of probability of default among six data mining methods. From the perspective of risk management, the result of predictive accuracy of the estimated probability of default will be more valuable than the binary result of classification - credible or not credible clients. With the real probability of default as the response variable (Y), and the predictive probability of default as the independent variable (X), the simple linear regression result (Y = A + BX) shows that the forecasting model produced by artificial neural network has the highest coefficient of determination; its regression intercept (A) is close to zero, and regression coefficient (B) to one. Therefore, among the six data mining techniques, artificial neural network is the only one that can accurately estimate the real probability of default. There are 30.000 instances in the data.

Also, class imbalance problem requirement is satisfied with the ratio 3.52.

SGB_3['MAPE'] = pd.DataFrame(results['3.Task Stochastic Gradient Boosting'],columns = ['Parameters', 'Train Score', 'MAPE','RMSE'])['MAPE']
SGB_3['RMSE'] = pd.DataFrame(results['3.Task Stochastic Gradient Boosting'],columns = ['Parameters', 'Train Score', 'MAPE','RMSE'])['RMSE']

Learning = np.array(SGB_3['Learning Rate']).astype('str')
Depth = np.array(SGB_3['Depth']).astype('str')
tree = np.array(SGB_3['Number of Trees']).astype('str')
space=np.full(36,'-')
Learn = np.char.add(Learning,space)
Depth_Learn = np.char.add(Learn,Depth)
dls = np.char.add(Depth_Learn,space)
full = np.char.add(dls,tree)
SGB_3['Parameters'] = full

At first glance, different alpha values for lasso logistic show very remarkable difference in score and accuracy. The score and accuracy in the first graph, increases with the log10 of alpha. In other words, alpha 1.0 gives the best result which is approximately 0.90 accuracy, for logistic lasso with 1.Data.

In the top-right graph, complexity parameter and minimal number of observations per tree leaf take different values. By looking graph, it can be said that complexity-parameter has remarkable effect on the results rather than min. num. of observations per tree leaf parameter. When the complexity parameter increases from 0.01 to 0.1, score and accuracy decreases dramatically in the graph regardless of the other parameter.On the other hand, when the min.num. of observations per tree leaf parameter is 10, score and accuracy have the better result than other values-20 and 30.

Moreover, according to left-bottom graph, random forest gives better result than lasso and decision tree. However, in training data results are same regardless of number of feature, also it can be said that overfitting exists for this data. But, test results in terms of accuracy are still successfull. They are approximately 0.94.

Finally, in the stochastic gradient boosting algorithm, there is overfit in some parameters for the training data. However, the best result is reached with learning rate 0.1, depth 15 and number of trees 200. The test accuracy with those parameters in the last algorithm is the best among all algorithms with the accuracy value of 0.99.

For the 2.Data, different alpha values for lasso logistic give same result in score and accuracy. Altough there is no very huge difference between score and accuracy, interestingly test accuracy is slightly better than train score. This case does not change with any alpha value I try. This situation may be stem from data.

In the top-right graph, complexity parameter and min. samples leaf parameter take different values. By looking graph, it can be said that train score has the best result when complexity parameter and min. samples leaf take the value of 0.0001 and 10, respectively. On the other hand, test accuracy has the best result when complexity parameter is 0.001 and 0.01 with the value of 0.82. Also, both train score and test accuracy have the worst results when the complexity parameter is 0.1. For those reasons, it may be the better strategy to set complexity parameter as 0.001 or 0.01, in these points, train score and test accuracy are getting closer to each other.

Moreover, according to left-bottom graph, random forest gives better result than lasso and decision tree. Train score increases with the increase in number of feature and this converges to 0.90. On the other hand, test accuracy is approximately 0.82 for all number of feature.

Finally, in the stochastic gradient boosting algorithm, there is increasing trend with minor decreasing trend. This trend stems from learning rate, when the learning rate reach the 0.1 learning rate, train score has the best result. For the minor decreasing trend, depth has inverse effect on the score. When the depth increases with constant learning rate and number of trees, score is decreasing. Also, number of trees is positive effect on the score. However, parameters have remarkable impact on the train score, test accuracy is not change significantly in the graph. The accuracy is approximately 0.82 among all parameter combination.

For the 3.Data whose output is continuous so there is a regression problem, different alpha values for lasso cause very different results in terms of score and MAPE. When the alpha is 10^-2, train score and MAPE value of test data give the best result for lasso regression. Also, it should be noticed that score in regression problem is R^2. Moreover, there is no interesting case between training and test data, there must be an inverse relation between score and MAPE values. This is true for all algorithms in the graphs.

In the top-right graph, complexity parameter and min. samples leaf parameter take different values. By looking graph, it can be said complexity parameter does not affect the results remarkably because with different complexity parameter except the last one 0.1, results are approximately same. On the other hand, increase in the min. samples leaf parameter affects inversely results. With the value of 10 for min. samples leaf, algorithm gives the best result, it is 0.94 for train score and 6.8 for MAPE in the test data.

Moreover, according to left-bottom graph, random forest gives better result than lasso and decision tree. Train score increases with the increase in number of feature and this converges to 0.965. On the other hand, MAPE value is decreasing with the incease in the number of feature. The best result is achieved when the number of feature equals to 65 for this data.

Finally, in the stochastic gradient boosting algorithm, there is increasing trend with minor decreasing trend for R^2 in train data. This trend stems from learning rate, when the learning rate reach the 0.1 learning rate, train score has the best result. For the minor decreasing trend, depth has inverse effect on the score. When the depth increases with constant learning rate and number of trees, score is decreasing. Also, number of trees is positive effect on the score. Efficiently, when parameters have remarkable impact on the train score, MAPE value for test data change significantly in the graph.

QUESTIONS¶

a. Is the cross-validation error rate of different approaches consistent with the test error rate?

In all algotihms, train score and test accuracy show similar behavior with different parameters. However, in some cases, while train score is increasing test accuracy reachs its limit. But, still, it can be said that, error rate of different approaches are consinstent with the test error rate, generally.

b. What is your observation about the performance of the classifiers over all datasets?

As I ordered the algorithms before for all datasets, stochastic gradient boosting gives really very good result for test accuracy. Besides, the second best algorithm is random forest. Then, decision three is third one and finally, lasso is the worst one among all of them.

c. How would you compare training and test error? Is there any indication of underfitting or overfitting?

I compare the training and test error as follows: their trend or behavior with different parameter or parameters combination. In some cases, while training score still increasing, test accuracy does not change remarkably. To illustate, for 4.Data with stochastic gradient boosting algorithm, train score reach the 1.0; however, test accuracy cannot increase itself. This situation is overfitting.

Besides, for 2.Data there is underfitting for lasso logistic, test accuracy gives better result than training score with all different alphas. However, this case does not happen in any other case.

To sum up, this behavior and results are indications of underfittin and overfitting as I explained.
